Parliament did not support an amendment to free Tymoshenko
Ukraine's parliament has rejected a proposal to repeal the amendment to the Criminal Code section condemning opposition leader Yulia Tymoshenko.
The amendment would open the door to the release of the minister, but MPs rejected the proposal to reduce penalties for economic crimes in the second reading.
In October, Tymoshenko was sentenced to seven years in prison for allegedly signing a deal with Russia disadvantageous for Ukraine on the purchase of natural gas.
The ruling is not yet final, and the appeals court is required to review it in December.
Tymoshenko was convinced that it was a political revenge of the regime, and even in the West doubts have arisen about the impartiality of the court.
The proposal to withdraw paragraph 365 of the Criminal Code condemning the former Prime Minister was supported by 147 deputies in the vote.
226 votes were required for approval.
