Iranian students are willing to die for their country’s nuclear program.
They formed a human shield.
Several hundred university students formed human shields around nuclear facilities in Iran.
With their gesture they want to express their support for their country’s nuclear program in the face of a possible Israeli attack.
The students began praying at noon on Tuesday in front of the facility and then chanted death slogans to the US and Israel.
Several hundred university students formed human shields in the Iranian city of Isfahan around the nuclear technology center where uranium is being worked.
They intend to show that they are willing to defend their country’s nuclear program with their own lives.
The International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA), in a recent report, found that Iran, according to all indications, is striving to obtain nuclear weapons.
There is talk in Israel of a possible attack on Iranian nuclear facilities.
The students began praying at noon in front of the Isfahan nuclear facilities and then launched death slogans against the US and Israel.
In the event of an attack, the aim of which would be to paralyze Iran’s nuclear program, Israeli sources say not only the Isfahan nuclear power plant, but also the Natanz facilities, where uranium is enriched, would be reached.
Daily menu of an obese child: no breakfast and dinner sausages
More than a third of children between the ages of 9 and 13 have overweight problems, where overweight affects 9% of the school population and obesity affects 5%.
Obese children mostly come from families with an unhealthy lifestyle, according to current research.
It shows again the importance of the environment where it is grown for a healthy development of the person, as well as the models that serve as a reference.
At the table, obese children eat, for example, sausages at least twice as often as children of normal weight families.
For dinner, more than 19% of obese people had eaten French fries the day before the analysis, which is linked to the prevention program "Obesity is not a coincidence".
In families of overweight children, there is no practice of sports, which is applicable to most families today, where only 15% of children responded that their parents, at least once a week, find time for physical exercise.
A survey of 900 children
The survey was conducted at the end of last school year and involved almost 900 elementary school children from all over the Czech Republic.
It was already the second edition of the program "Obesity is not a coincidence", which supports the General Health Insurance Company and the company Unilever.
So far, more than 12,000 children have participated in the project from the 4th to the 8th year.
A proper diet and plenty of family exercise are determining factors, which significantly reduce the number of overweight and even obese children.
“Only half of the children surveyed have responded that they have five meals a day according to the regimen: breakfast, lunch, lunch, snack and dinner, which is one of the basic conditions for a healthy diet,” the survey found.
No breakfast but with built-in for dinner
Specialists warn that, in a healthy development, are also important details, which also count, such as having a fixed time for breakfast with the family.
In the Czech Republic, however, only 23% of schoolchildren’s families have breakfast at the same time.
In most families, everyone eats breakfast alone.
But the worst thing was to find out that in 10% of households nothing is breakfast.
Breakfast is, however, the basis of a proper daily diet.
The study shows that in families of obese children, insane French fries are consumed much more often.
Almost everyone - regardless of weight - drinks sweet soft drinks on a daily basis (70%).
As a rule, more than 40% of the children surveyed play sports, however, among their parents this result is reduced to less than half, only 15%.
Make your own diet
The next phase of the study allowed the chosen boys (204 boys and 172 girls from 13 schools) to create their own diets from all possible offers according to their tastes and opinions.
“The dietary preferences of Czech children aged between 12 and 15 years, from the point of view of a healthy diet, are far from ideal.”
Among his favorite foods are pasta, meat and sweets.
“The popularity of sweet soft drinks is especially alarming,” the study’s final report warns.
As the main food, the palm takes the pasta and follows closely the poultry meat.
Practically, children always reject legumes and the taste for fish and vegetables is very low.
Changes to Healthy Habits
At the same time, the study shows that children are willing to change their eating habits if they receive the right information.
"In the control group of the study participants, who filled out the questionnaire after completing the prevention program "Obesity is not a coincidence", there was in many cases a significant change in favor of the principles of a healthy diet," the study notes.
It draws attention, for example, to sweet sodas, where many children would begin to prefer normal and running water.
Children would also more often choose poultry and fish for the main meal in the questionnaire and restrict the consumption of sweet food and flour derivatives.
