Brand story:
The innovative IBM begins its second century of existence
If someone were to search for a term that would define IBM’s strategy with great precision, the most approximate would be “long-term.”
For the general public, IBM is the symbol of a technological revolution, a company that is perceived as current and yet has already passed a hundred years since its foundation.
The basis of this long-standing placist character was laid by the first head of the firm, the visionary Thomas J. Watson Sr.
He already coined the slogan that many problems in the world have a solution if people are willing to think.
Its motto "Think!" became its seal, around which the life of the future giant will be built (it was also the title of an internal magazine that IBM began publishing in 1935).
Watson was also the basis of a carefully built company culture.
“For us, IBM involves long-term thinking, a continuous movement toward the future.
IBM has survived and prospered for a hundred years for that reason, because it remained true to its basic principles, but without fear of the changes around it.
That has allowed us, during our first century, to transform technology, business and society.
We look forward to prospering even further in our second century,” said Samuel J. Palmisano, the company’s current director.
A sophisticated system
Watson, as early as the 1930s, took care of his employees as the entrepreneur of Bata in the Czech Republic (IBM employees were among the first American workers to enjoy paid vacations, insurance, stylish uniforms and a sophisticated remuneration system that rewarded top inventors and sellers.
The same long-term sophistication is maintained by IBM in the customer relationship.
From the very beginning, the company knew how to discover talents (being one of the first companies in the world to end any type of discrimination, it could choose without problems).
In line with the anti-discrimination strategy is IBM’s current plan, whereby Palmisano will be replaced next year by a woman: Virginia Rometty.
She has been working at IBM for thirty years, where she has been head of sales, marketing and strategy.
Over the past few years, IBM has participated in so-called virtual meetings, a rain of ideas online, from which countless future strategies and innovations emerge.
It is not surprising that ideas abound, as almost half a million people work at the firm.
An institution with a good reputation
The fixed position in the business provides the company with a strong internal and external image.
"From the beginning, IBM maintained a concept of an institution rather than a technology company," says Harvard Business School economics professor and author of the book on IBM Rosabeth Moss Kanter.
“IBM is not a technology company, but a company that tries to solve business problems for users of technology,” said George Colony of Forrester Research.
As the company itself says, there is a difference between entering the business and directly creating a business.
IBM – or the “Great Green” – as it is known in the U.S. familiarly because of its logo, has become in the last hundred years one of the largest companies in the world.
It is possibly the most versatile technology company (it develops both equipment and programs, infrastructures and web hosting services within a wide range of services, ranging from servers to nanotechnology).
It holds the largest number of patents from all U.S. technology companies, and five of its employees have received the Nobel Prize.
Among his inventions are the ATM, payment cards, financial exchanges, barcodes and floppy disks.
This year IBM has become the second technology firm by market capitalization (the first is Apple), when it first surpassed Microsoft in 1996.
Looking to the future
Not all products and innovations have just satisfied customers’ taste and the moment (IBM did not bet on its own operating system, OS/2, Prodigy online services or IBM PCjr computers).
“If your business is based on moving forward, it cannot be emotionally anchored in the past,” Samuel J. Palmisano acknowledged.
That’s why IBM has no problem building its bases on other platforms (and also, if they don’t work, abandons them).
And this is the difference from the competition, Microsoft, which basically keeps and always falls exclusively with Windows.
Technology of the future
In terms of sales, IBM is mainly dedicated to services, of which about a fifth are programs and another fifth are equipment.
However, as late as 1990, equipment accounted for more than half of the supplier share.
As of 2000, IBM has sold low-yield assets worth a total of $15 billion. During the same period, it has invested $58 billion in the purchase of future technology.
Investments have continued since 2008, when the modern global financial crisis first manifested itself.
IBM is acting on the premise of its first boss, Thomas J. Watson, who increased investments during the great economic crisis of the 29th century.
It seems that so far the IBM company has managed to cope with the crisis.
The value of IBM’s shares since the beginning of 2008 has grown stratospherically up to 120%, the company’s net profit has not stopped increasing.
The currency of IBM is to change everything except its value.
One can therefore expect that when the next crisis comes, this flexible giant will endure.
IBM History: From the Cheese Cutter to Spaceflight
IBM (International Business Machines) was founded in New York a hundred years ago, its original name being Computing Tabulating Recording Corporation.
The name IBM was adopted as early as 1924 - originally it was a brand used in the branches of Canada and South America.
The basis for the birth of IBM stems from the merger of four companies dating back to the 1880s.
He owned inventions such as the famous "check clock", which allows to control the entry and exit of employees.
The architect of the new company was businessman Charles Ranlett Flint, who until 1930 also chaired its supervisory board.
Flint enlisted the head of a competing company, Thomas J. Watson, to assist him with the management of the company.
The new leader eclipsed the founder of IBM (Watson’s ideas remain the firm foundation on which corporate culture and identity are built).
Watson ran the company until 1952.
IBM, as its name suggests, started with the production and sale of all kinds of business appliances, from meat and cheese cutters to cash registers.
During the first four years Watson led the company, revenue doubled by $9 million and the company began to expand rapidly across the continents.
Watson was so crucial to the company that, after nearly forty years in the chief’s chair, he was replaced by his son, Thomas Watson Junior.
Under his leadership, IBM began working on the development of artificial intelligence and developed the first programming language.
In the 1960s IBM staff and computers helped NASA guide flights into space (to Mercury, Saturn, and in 1969 the famous flight to the Moon).
In 1964, IBM developed the first generation of computers, the IBM System/360 series.
The classic "pieces", which established the computer standard of the time, came to market under the name IBM 5150 in 1981.
Twenty years later, IBM sold its computer production to the Chinese company Lenovo, which, in turn, acquired the consulting part of the company Pricewaterhouse Coopers and began to offer complete advice and high value-added services.
The strategy that IBM has paid for these last three years is the Smarter Planet concept, that is, “a smarter planet.”
Its aim is to make more rational use of the technology, although the areas have not yet been planned and the circumstances have not improved, for example, in terms of transport and city administration.
For the commerce sector, IBM recently introduced the “Smart Commerce” platform that allows retailers to manage the entire business cycle.
IBM has a long history in this country.
As early as 1932, it opened a branch in then-Czechoslovakia, the first country to have it in Central and Eastern Europe.
Today, the IBM <0xC4><0x8C>R also operates the strategic outsourcing center in Brno.
The headquarters for Central and Eastern Europe is in Prague. Also here is a world-renowned research team working with voice recognition.
