How travel prices have evolved since 1989
Until 1989 there were only five state-authorized travel agencies in Czechoslovakia: <0xC4><0x8C>edok, Sporturist, CKM, Rekrea and Autoturist.
The travel agencies of that time in most cases sold trips only to the socialist bloc, as trips to the West were very restricted.
Czech tourists therefore went on holiday to the beaches of the GDA (German Democratic Republic), the Soviet Union, (Sochi in Crimea in the Black Sea) to Bulgaria and Romania (both in the Black Sea) and Hungary (Balaton).
A positive exception was the period between 1962 and 1972, when one could travel to Yugoslavia, however, after the Yugoslav regime leaned west and the trips of Czech tourists were then quite restricted.
A great paradox of socialism was the fact that the citizens of the socialist bloc (i.e. also the Czechoslovaks) were not allowed to travel freely and individually even through the socialist countries.
If a citizen wanted to travel individually, for example, to Poland or the Soviet Union, he needed an invitation letter, if not, individual travel was not possible.
Travel agencies at that time also offered trips to the West, but one had to queue up with a sleeping bag and spend the whole night like that, or have "good acquaintances" at the agency.
Still, not everything was won.
The so-called "promise of change" that was the condition for trips to the West, was not granted to the "politically unreliable people", who thus could not travel at all.
The Czechoslovak currency was not a freely convertible currency and, without exchange guarantee, it was not possible to obtain the resources (the Western currency) to travel to the West.
The vast majority of Czechs spent their holidays in their own country, so there were a large number of cottages and summer houses, which the Czechs acquired. This custom still persists.
The Czech way of travelling has undergone a genuine revolution since 1989.
While until 1989 for us it was no longer going to spend the holidays in the GDA or Bulgaria, last year the Czechs made 4.5 million vacation trips to countries around the world.
It is a great paradox, of which we are no longer aware today, the fact that until 1989 one could not travel freely to the currently favorite destination, Croatia, because it was part of Yugoslavia at that time.
In the early 1990s, visa-free travel to neighboring Western European states was imposed, prompting a huge wave of short-term visits, especially to Vienna or Germany.
The Czechoslovaks, for a long time, did not look tired of excursions to the West, everyone wanted to see it at least for a moment.
For example, in Paris, groups of Czechs slept in the parks in tents, since our income at the time did not allow us to pay for a hotel or pension.
A typical feature of the Czechs of that time was to take food (canned goods, sausages, etc.) with them to save money.
Another important moment was the introduction of the convertibility of the Czech crown, so that our tourists could finally, after decades, freely buy Western currency.
Our standard of living was increasing and with it also the average wages, which around 1997 caused an increase in the demand for travel.
With the increase in the demand for travel agencies began, from 1997 on a regular basis, to prepare the trips using the connections of charter flights, which made the prices of the trips incredibly low compared to the past, thanks to the possibility of obtaining discounts for the volume of passengers.
By the end of the 1990s, the Czechs were already traveling visa-free to almost all developed countries except the US, which further simplified our travel.
Another interesting moment in the history of post-revolutionary tourism happened already in 2000, when it was organized, thanks to a huge demand, the first direct flight from the Czech Republic to an exotic country, and went to Thailand.
Since that year, every year, direct charter flights with Czech tourists to distant and hot countries depart. This winter will already fly directly from the Czech Republic to 12 exotic destinations.
The exotic countries currently visit them about 100 thousand Czechs a year.
Another interesting moment of this era, which symbolizes our post-revolutionary development, came in 2008.
On November 17, 2008, the U.S. eliminated visas for Czech tourists, making our country one of the most developed countries in the world.
In 2008, the Czechs, for the first time in their history, have spent more than half of their holidays abroad (50.3%) and for the first time in their history, have spent more than 15 thousand Czech crowns per head on trips abroad, including expenses at the place of stay.
