7 Lessons From Steve Jobs’ Lost Interview, Shown in a Theater This Week
After the death of Steve Jobs on October 5, there were some who compared him to Henry Ford - distinguishing the genius of technology as the Great Modern Inventor.
But what Apple fans might find most revealing, in a recently rediscovered interview with Jobs that has been dusted off ahead of a series of special screenings in the biggest markets this week, is how much he understood this creative mind about business processes and product workflows.
He was certainly a designer, dreamer, and self-recognized hippie, but he was also a meticulous organizer and a flowchart junkie — a man who believed that many executives suffered “a disease that consists of thinking that a great idea is 90 percent of the work... [but] there’s a huge amount of work between a great idea and a great product.”
In 1995, Bob Cringley was developing the television series The Triumph of the Nerds about the dawn of the personal computer, and sat for more than an hour with Jobs for an extensive and rare conversation.
At the time, it had been barely 10 years since Jobs had been forced to leave Apple, and he was already working intensively at his new NeXT computer company, waiting for the popular adoption of the Internet.
While a small part of Cringley’s interview was used on Nerds, he said the originals of the interview disappeared during his transport.
It was only after Jobs’s death that a full VHS copy was discovered in the director’s garage.
This archive material, slightly re-edited, is the basis of Steve Jobs: The 68-minute lost interview, which arrives at Landmark cinemas this Wednesday and Thursday.
For someone known to hate in-depth interviews, Jobs here seems surprisingly willing to expose his technological philosophies and business strategies.
And very thoughtful.
At four different points throughout the interview, there are great silences between questions and answers – from 10 to 15 seconds of reflections, where Jobs is clearly weighing his thoughts, seeking accuracy.
There are also times when Jobs’s perfectionism comes to the surface, where he seems impatient due to Cringely’s questions, pushing him to go faster toward more important topics or arguments.
Filmed before the era of Pixar, the iPod or the iPhone, there’s something strangely prophetic about The Lost Interview, when Jobs evaluates what other companies do right and wrong, and offers his own vision of the future of computing.
It’s one thing to read posthumous assessments of Jobs’ career, but there’s something raw and inspiring about the Jobs we see here, the eager dreamer on the verge of greatness.
He has a vision of how things can and should be.
Not long after I explained everything in detail here, it was and it did.
A quick summary of seven notable sequences from The Lost Interview:
About how you learned to run a business:
“Over the years in the business, I’ve always asked, ‘Why do you do things?’ and the answers invariably give you are, ‘Oh, that’s just the way it’s done.’
No one knows why he does what he does, in business no one thinks about things very deeply.
That's what I found.
Jobs details his efforts to simplify Apple’s accounting.
Bewildered by the way costs were recorded - often starting with a "standard cost" that was done in good faith, and then adjusted with a "variable" - he developed an automated factory that ensured that they could determine commercial costs in detail.
The joke to the Pope:
Jobs narrates the “Blue Box” he himself built with Steve Wozniak – a device that allowed people to effectively hack into the phone company and make long-distance calls for free.
It has been widely written about the device, but Jobs’ euphoria here in describing the Blue Box as an act of empowerment is contagious.
He describes how he and Wozniak tested the box using a public phone, making a call, and then connecting from one AT&T network to another, while creating a loop with as many satellites as possible.
“We were wrapping things around the world half a dozen times and you screamed through the public phone and came back a minute later to the public phone next door,” Jobs says with a laugh.
“We were young and what we learned was that we could build something ourselves that could control billions of dollars of infrastructure around the world.”
The two of us, we didn’t know much, but we could build a little thing that could control a giant thing – it was an incredible lesson, and I don’t think there would ever have been an Apple without it.
Jobs goes on to describe a glorious joke that he and Wozniak almost abandon, calling the Vatican through the Blue Box in the middle of the night and asking to speak with the Pope, while making his best imitation of Henry Kissinger.
As several members of the Catholic hierarchy were summoned in the middle of the night to speak with the U.S. diplomat, the two burst into shrieks just before the pope himself was awakened to go answer the phone.
About falling in love with technology (and selling by phone with Bill Hewlett):
At the age of 12, hunting for spare parts to build a frequency counter, he looked for Bill Hewlett in the phone book and made a call to him.
Shortly after his 20-minute phone conversation, Jobs got a part-time summer job at Hewlett-Packard.
“That was a remarkable influence on me, it was the only company I had seen at that age and it shaped my vision of what a company was and how well they treated their employees.”
Jobs later became one of HP’s employees who visited the company’s research labs in Palo Alto, where he saw “the first desktop computer ever made.”
It was as big as a suitcase, it had a small cathode-ray tube screen, and I fell in love with it.
I would get a trip to HP as a teenager and waste time with that machine and write programs for it.
On improvising innovation:
At various points in the interview, Jobs talks about inventing new products on the go.
Soon in his career, as he devoted himself to selling a handful of motherboards, he was asked by a client if he could assemble the whole team.
Working with only 30 credit days, I had to figure out the assembly and delivery of the finished devices.
Later, while at Apple, he recalled the struggles he faced in developing a computer mouse:
“I remember having dramatic arguments ... I was shouted that it would take five years [to create a mouse that would cost $300], and I got tired and went out and found a designer.
Ninety days later, we had a mouse that we could build for $15 and that was totally reliable.
On big companies losing strength:
Long before he led Apple’s renaissance, Jobs prophetically predicted how many industry leaders would stumble upon his vision, and lose control of their market share.
“Say you work at IBM or Xerox, so you make better copiers and printers, and what?”
You have the monopoly of market share, so the company is no longer successful.
Sales and marketing departments increase success, so it is this kind of people who end up running the companies and the people in charge of the products are kicked out of the decision-making forum.
The genius of the products that led to that monopoly position rots because of people who do not have the notion of good products vs. bad products - the knowledge of the necessary trade.
That's what happened at Xerox...
Xerox could have taken over the entire computer industry.
It could have been ten times its size, it could have been the Microsoft of the 90s...
They took the defeat of victory.
About innovation as an artistic expression:
“There’s a huge amount of work between a great idea and a great product... as the great idea evolves, it changes and grows.”
You learn a lot about the subtleties of it.
There are sacrifices you have to make – some things you can’t do that electrons do, glass does them, robots do them, factories do them.
You have to keep 5,000 things in your brain — these concepts — adjust them all at once.
In the end it all comes down to taste – it comes down to trying to expose yourself to the best that a team of humans has done, and then trying to adapt those things to what you’re doing.
Picasso said that good artists copy, great artists steal.
We have never been ashamed of stealing great ideas.
What made the Macintosh great in part was that the people who were working on it were musicians, poets, artists, zoologists, historians, who happened to be the best computer scientists in the world.
If it wasn’t for computer science, I might be doing wonderful things in other fields.
Scalia and Thomas dine with health care law rivals as court accepts case
The day the Supreme Court met behind closed doors to examine the politically controversial question of whether they would accept the challenge to President Obama’s health care law, two of his judges, Antonin Scalia and Clarence Thomas, were hosted at a dinner sponsored by the law firm that will expose the case to the high court.
