Stopping the development and further testing of the F35 could generate some $80 billion in savings over 10 years, but its supporters say it is the next vital step in improving and addressing potential threats from China and other rivals.
How to detect a lie
A look at the most recent headlines tells us how serious and ubiquitous deception and lies are in daily life.
Republican presidential candidate Herman Cain is busy exchanging allegations of sexual harassment with several women; each side accuses the other of lying.
Pennsylvania State University administrators have been charged with perjury for allegedly hiding reports that a retired football coach was sexually assaulting children.
Last week, French President Nicolas Sarkozy was “caught” with an open microphone claiming to U.S. President Barack Obama that Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu is a liar.
Lying has destroyed careers and convulsed countries.
Congressman for New York and Internet exhibitor Anthony Weiner made the ridicule with his denials quickly refuted by the irrefutable proof.
Former presidential candidate John Edwards has been charged with campaign funding violations related to the cover-up of an extramarital affair.
And, again, no one who lives it will ever forget the media circus unleashed by President Bill Clinton by lying during his second term about his sexual relationship with Monica Lewinsky.
There are widespread legends about traps in school and university exams.
There have been cases where teachers have given test responses to students in order to be better seen in their performance assessments.
Mentors who should be teaching the opposite are sending the message that lying and cheating are acceptable.
How much deception do we find ourselves?
On any given day, studies show that they can lie to you anywhere from 10 to 200 times.
That's for sure, many of those lies are godly lies.
Another study showed that strangers lied three times in the first 10 minutes they met.
Detecting lies, or “the location of lies,” is an essential skill that we all must acquire, for both personal and professional reasons.
Far from being a board game similar to, for example, Charada, where the goal is to exclaim: "I have you", the detection of deception is a branch of serious knowledge based on scientific data obtained during the last six decades in prestigious universities that carried out in-depth research projects, especially in psychology and physiology.
One of the results of the research is that the old myths about lying have been rebuffed.
Liars do look into their eyes.
They don’t always stutter, babble, blush, or worry.
Nor can it be concluded that liars are difficult to detect or unmask.
A trained lie detector can come to the truth by learning about the structure of the statement, microfacial expressions, question formation, and times.
I spent several years probing scientific discoveries about deception in the vast and ever-emerging body of knowledge, and it was clear that deception detection is a modern technique that is easy to learn and helps navigate our complex world – especially if your professional responsibilities include hiring, interviewing, or negotiating.
Good liars have the ability to read others well, making them feel comfortable, managing their own emotions, and intuitively feeling how others perceive them.
We know from research that extroverts lie more than introverts, that men tell more "self-oriented lies," while women tell more "other-oriented" lies -- usually to protect someone's feelings -- that married people lie less often to their partners than people who are not married (but who tell their lies).
We also know that if you are perceived as a wrongdoer, others will feel less guilty by lying to you.
How do I know if someone is lying?
First, observe the usual behavior of the subject.
This is called “creating a baseline.”
It helps to provide reference points for later measurement of changes.
Observe the subject’s posture, laughter, and vocal characteristic.
It’s best to know if someone normally knocks with their foot all the time so as not to make unfair accusations when they see their feet knocking in the middle of the meeting.
Next, look for deceptive, verbal, and nonverbal behavioral groups.
Consider these behavioral groups as alarm signals, not proof of deception.
People who cheat can freeze the upper body by trying to remember their story, can point their feet toward the door, lean toward an exit, change their posture significantly, or exhibit a “post-interview blur” — that exaggerated sigh of relief and change of posture once all the difficult questions are over.
Often interrogators falsely state that the interview is over only to seek that post-interview relief.
Also pay attention to the subject’s vocabulary.
Scott Peterson put his foot down and used the time he spent claiming that his murdered wife was alive, launching a nationwide search for her.
People who cheat can also use a differentiating language: “I didn’t have sex with that woman... Miss Lewinsky” or repeat a difficult question entirely.
The most common verbal indicators are subtle.
Someone can use a lot of "restrictive language" when answering a difficult question: "Well... to tell the truth... to what I know... to my understanding."
This makes the response a perception rather than a fact and is often a warning sign.
There is no magic formula for detecting lies, but developing skills to discover deception is possible.
These skills will improve anyone’s chances to avoid being victimized by scam artists in their professional and personal lives.
