The new Italian government will be formed on Wednesday.
The appointed Prime Minister, Mario Monti, will meet tomorrow with the President of Italy to present the new government that will face a crisis that has put that country on the brink of economic disaster.
Italian Prime Minister-designate Mario Monti will meet with Italy’s president on Wednesday to present the new government that will face a crisis that has put Italy on the brink of economic disaster and put the entire eurozone in jeopardy.
A statement from the presidential palace announced that Monti, appointed on Sunday, will meet Wednesday with President Giorgio Napolitano to confirm that he can form a government.
He is expected to present a cabinet composed mostly of technocrats, although it is unclear when the new executive will take office.
Monti said he will present to the president the outcome of his talks with political parties in his bid to form a government.
"I want to confirm my absolute confidence in our country's ability to overcome this difficult phase," he told reporters.
Monti did not explicitly say he would be able to form a government, but the tone of his comments indicated that the obstacles had been overcome.
The “framework is now well-delineated,” he added.
Monti has completed the process of forming a government in less than three days, much less than usual, as Italy grapples with a political and financial crisis that has pushed its debt costs to unsustainable levels.
The new administration led by former European Commissioner Monti must approve a tough austerity package demanded by European leaders to regain the battered confidence in Italy.
Underscoring pressure on Monti to rush ahead, market instability put the yield on Italian BTP bonds at 10 years above 7 percent, the level at which Greece and Ireland were forced to bail out.
Emma Marcegaglia, leader of the Italian employer Confindustria, told the press after meeting with Monti: “We said we would be very supportive of this government.”
We believe that this government is the last chance for Italy to get out of this emergency situation.
Monti’s chances of success were considerably boosted by the backing of Silvio Berlusconi’s PDL party, whom the crisis forced to resign on Saturday.
“We believe that Professor Monti’s efforts are destined to have a good result,” Angelino Alfano, secretary of the centre-right party, told reporters.
