At the press conference, the head of the SCT, Pérez J<0xC3><0xA1>come, listed six relevant elements in the research:
Visual flight:
According to the aeronautical regulations the flight was conducted under the visual flight rules, this implies that the crew must have visibility during the flight and the terrain.
Weather conditions:
The reports at the AICM located conditions suitable for takeoff, as the aircraft advanced towards the border area between the DF and the State of Mexico presented layers of low-altitude cloudiness.
Selected routes:
Due to cloud conditions, the crew is likely to have sought a zone of lower elevation and greater visibility towards the Cuernavaca valley.
Location of the impact.
The impact coordinates and the last radar record coincide, probably before the impact there was no loss of control or alteration in the flight path.
Dispersion of aircraft debris in a reduced area:
The information available so far suggests that the impact occurred on a straight and sideways trajectory.
The pattern of debris dispersion of the aircraft makes it possible to assume that the helicopter was impacted on the ground under conditions of structural integrity.
No evidence of fire or explosion has been detected:
At the site of the accident, no evidence remains of any kind of explosion or fire in the wreckage.
The latest research results indicate that he may have had multiple contacts with the ground.
During the field work, pieces of the aircraft have been found at an elevation of 9,200 feet above average sea level, the terrain has a slope ranging from seven degrees to 30 degrees of inclination.
The photographs show the sequence in which it is expected to be disarticulated along such a path.
The information provides elements that appear to indicate that the helicopter may have had multiple impacts on the ground.
After a thorough search in a wider area than the cordoned-off site, around the accident, no scattered pieces of the aircraft have been found, strengthening the presumption that the impact was presented in conditions of structural integrity.
MSS Announces Protocol to Find Obesity Gene
Leads Social Security research to discover obesity gene in children and young people; is supported by IPN specialists
The Mexican Institute of Social Security (IMSS) announced that it is conducting research to discover the obesity gene in children and young people, called the 'Genetics of Childhood and Adolescent Obesity' protocol, which will allow for markers associated with overweight.
In a statement, Miguel Cruz L<0xC3><0xB3>pez, head of the Medical Research Unit in Biochemistry of the Hospital of Specialities of the National Medical Center XXI Century, explained that a multidisciplinary team of doctors, nurses, nutritionists and social workers was integrated.
This team is supported by specialists and postgraduate students from the National Institute of Public Health (INSP) and the Center for Research and Advanced Studies (Cinvestav) of the National Polytechnic Institute (IPN).
The research invites the population, whether or not entitled, to attend the participating sports units of the IMSS in the Valley of Mexico, where the tests are carried out to minors, every Saturday from 8:00 a.m.
He stressed that the protocol began in the Cuauhtémoc Sports Unit (State of Mexico Poniente) and that since October 8, the activity is carried out in the Nezahualc<0xC3><0xB3>yolt Sports Unit (State of Mexico Oriente).
Once the goal of gathering 500 or 600 children is met, the study will continue in the Independent Sports Unit (south of the Federal District) and finally in the Morelos Sports Unit (north of the Federal District).
He explained that the purpose of this research is to know the components and the importance of genetics with regard to the development of obesity and identify in Mexican children and young people risk factors to prevent the appearance of chronic degenerative diseases.
On the occasion of World Diabetes Day on 14 November, he said that the goal is to bring together 3,000 children and young people between the ages of six and 14, with the consent and supervision of their parents, for the implementation of specific questionnaires on nutrition.
They will also be asked about physical activity and family history of diseases, in order to avoid risk factors that trigger conditions such as diabetes or kidney failure.
He explained that on Saturdays anthropometric measurements (weight, size, waist circumference), blood pressure, glucose, triglycerides, cholesterol and insulin levels and genetics are applied to all participants (genes associated with childhood obesity are sought to be identified).
Cruz L<0xC3><0xB3>pez noted that this research is due to the concern of health professionals for the alarming weight gain in minors.
“The 1999 and 2006 health surveys indicated that in just six years there was an increase, in the case of boys, of 77 percent in obesity, and girls of 47 percent; in terms of overweight, there was also a dramatic rise,” said the IMSS specialist.
He indicated that the justification for the search for markers is based on the fact that the population of the country differs from others by its genetic history.
He reported that on average, the Mexican has 65 percent American Indian, 30 percent European and five percent African heritage and this condition is reflected in the genes associated with diabetes and excess weight.
He explained that in general, the genetics of obesity translates into the inability to burn the excess energy we consume (calories) and that it is stored in the form of fat.
The researcher explained that the direct benefit for the participants is the comprehensive evaluation of the children, which allows to detect if they present any degree of overweight or obesity.
Even, he said, the presence of dark-colored folds (acanthosis) in the neck and forearm, which indicate the likelihood of suffering metabolic alterations and even prediabetes.
The information is handled confidentially, doctors deliver it in writing to the parents, to whom each of the measurements and lifestyle changes they must make to prevent diseases are explained.
Cruz L<0xC3><0xB3>pez explained that there are three main components that cause overweight, obesity and other chronic conditions: sedentary, which is the lack of daily physical activity, staying most of the day sitting in front of the TV and using means of transport instead of walking short distances.
It is also due to the high caloric intake, i.e. the higher consumption of sugary drinks, carbohydrates (cooks, bread, pizza, hamburger, etc.) with high fat and protein content and the genetics that is analyzed in this protocol.
Asphalt from UNAM would avoid bumps
Rafael Herrera, a researcher at the UNAM Faculty of Chemistry, develops polymer-modified asphalts to produce a mixture with better performance, regardless of environmental and temperature conditions
If the signals sent by the pavement were attended to, it would not be necessary to repair about 200,000 bumps each rainy season in the Metropolitan Zone of the Valley of Mexico, warned Rafael Herrera N<0xC3><0xA1>jera, a researcher at the Faculty of Chemistry (FQ) of UNAM, who assured that if the process of construction and maintenance of a pavement could be eliminated by appropriate means.
At his conference A technological opinion of the bumps, dictated within the framework of the International Year of Chemistry, revealed that the laboratory in charge develops modified asphalts with polymers to produce a mixture with characteristics similar to those of asphalt, but with greater mechanical resistance, both at high and low temperatures.
Herrera N<0xC3><0xA1>jera estimated that this type of modified asphalt could be used in places where the weather is extremely hot, such as some cities in the north of the country, to improve its performance and, therefore, the formation of bumps.
He explained that asphalt, the heaviest part of oil, is a set of hydrocarbon molecules, some of high molecular weight, called asphaltenes, and others of low molecular weight, called maltenes, which together give the pavement its characteristic viscoelastic behavior.
The viscoelastic behavior of asphalt consists in that at high temperatures, close to 180 degrees, it behaves like a liquid, at 120 degrees centigrade its viscosity is very high and at 50 degrees centigrade it presents an almost solid state, while at very low temperatures, the asphalt becomes brittle, he added.
The above means that on the streets the resistance of the asphalt is not uniform, but is being modified during the day according to environmental and temperature conditions, the chemical engineering specialist warned.
The FQ researcher noted that the streets of Mexico City are mostly covered by flexible pavement, which consists of six layers of materials, the last three of which involve asphalt.
Among the most superficial layers is the asphalt folder, made up of small stones bathed in asphalt and then compacted.
Each of the stones that make up the folder, he pointed out, is bathed in asphalt.
By passing the vehicles and generating effort, it allows the forces to spread very well on the pavement.
If it were modified asphalt it would spread even better, the chemical engineer said.
On the asphalt folder, it abounded, a last layer called rolling folder is placed, which is made of a material of fine stone, that is, a sand that is also bathed in asphalt.
As it is the layer that will be in contact with the tires of the vehicles, it must have more mechanical force than the asphalt folder and provide friction on the way.
Being the part of the pavement that will receive and spread the efforts, the rolling folder also requires to have the right thickness and the material from which it is made must be taken care of.
Climate, especially humidity and temperature variations, are also a very important factor to consider, especially water, he said, because it significantly affects the performance of the asphalt folder.
When the soil is moistened, the water diffuses into the interior of the folder and it is difficult for it to come out, this causes a softening of all the layers of the pavement and, therefore, the formation of bumps.
In the process of forming a bump, he said, the first to wear out is the bearing film and only then the asphalt folder is affected, but the damage does not occur instantly, but it is a process that should be attended to at first signs with proper maintenance programs.
The also member of the National System of Researchers explained that the vehicular load is another important factor in the formation of bumps and, therefore, the thickness of each of the layers of the pavement must always be in relation to the vehicular load and ensure that it is complied with, to prevent the formation of bumps frequently.
Rafael Herrera warned that there is still a lot to research and work on asphalt, for example, asphalt emulsions, which in other countries are already even on the market and allow to repair the bumps easily and without the need to use high temperatures.
