Japan Reborn After Earthquake
GDP grows by 1.5% thanks to domestic consumption and puts an end to the spiral of falls that began in March
Since last March, the Japanese economy has been paralyzed, still convalescent by the devastating earthquake that became a nuclear crisis, the worst catastrophe the country has suffered since World War II.
The first estimates by the Government of Tokyo estimated the material losses at $300 billion, a blow that, despite the difficult global context, appears to have been mitigated.
After three consecutive quarters of declines, the data of Gross Domestic Product between July and September served to turn page, definitely: GDP increased by 1.5% compared to the previous quarter and 6% in annualized rate.
The second quarter – for the Japanese, the fiscal year begins in March 2012 – also represents the fastest pace of growth from January to March 2010.
The recovery is explained, in part, by the rebound in the purchase of machinery to restore the areas devastated by the earthquake and subsequent tsunami.
In fact, companies increased their investments by 1.1%, compared to the 0.9% decline in capital expenditures that was observed from January to March, the first setback after six months of uninterrupted increases.
However, the real revulsiveness of the Japanese economy is not based solely on the Keynesian impulse that invites us to take advantage of crises to strengthen – or rebuild – infrastructure, to use the shortages to grow from scratch.
Japan has awakened, above all, thanks to the evolution of domestic consumption, which currently accounts for 60% of Japanese GDP.
This variable climbed 1%, driven by increased spending on vehicles, travel and leisure activities.
The Stigma of the Yen
Tokyo has been entrusted to the domestic market, when the yen - the Japanese currency - has become one of the "refugee values" chosen by investors fleeing the euro zone debt crisis and the murky US forecasts, a privilege that weighs like a slab in the accounts of exporting companies.
With a stronger currency, products are more expensive abroad, a serious setback for a country whose economic flotation line is determined by the health of large technology groups.
Toyota or Sony, for example, spent their weak results between July and September on the yen.
As markets continue their siege of the EU’s peripheral countries, Yoshihiko Noda’s government is not lowering the guard.
“We need to pay attention to the risks that persist, such as the deterioration of some foreign economies, the impact of Thailand’s floods and the rapid appreciation of the yen,” said Motohisa Furukawa, Secretary of State for Economic Policy.
And, indeed, the prospects are not encouraging.
The Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development (OECD) said that most member countries showed stronger signs of economic slowdown in September.
The indicator that anticipates the turning points in the world economy highlighted that the major powers are slowing down.
As it dropped four tenths to 100.4 points, compared to 100.8 on August.
