The Nord Stream, the new gateway to Russian gas in Europe
The Nord Stream gas pipeline, which directly connects Western Europe with Russia via the Baltic Sea, has already been put into service.
It must supply gas to meet the needs of 30 million households.
Gazprom, the Russian gas giant, wanted to celebrate the event with great pomp.
Last Tuesday, more than 500 guests, including four Heads of State and Government, took part on the shores of the Baltic, between the music of the orchestra and a delicate buffet, at the inauguration of Nord Stream, the new gas pipeline that directly communicates, under the sea, Russia with Germany.
Symbolically, German Chancellor Angela Merkel, Russian President Dmitry Medvedev, French Prime Minister Fran<0xC3><0xA7>ois Fillon and his Dutch counterpart, Mark Rutte, have together turned the steering wheel of the valve that controls Russian gas entry into the Western European network.
With this new gas pipeline, every year 27.5 million cubic meters of additional Russian gas will arrive in Western Europe through a first had of 1,224 km connecting the St. Petersburg region with the Land of Mecklenburg-Pomerania.
A second pipeline should be completed by the end of 2012 that will supply a total of 55 billion cubic meters of gas, that is, enough to cover all French consumption.
In addition, we are already talking about the possibility of building a third tube for the same route.
For Gazprom, the timely completion of this huge work presents airs of victory.
Poland and the Baltic States had strongly opposed the project.
In fact, the Nord Stream will allow gas to be supplied directly to Germany, avoiding the land flow by third countries (Poland and Ukraine).
Suddenly, these two countries lose some of their power: for them, it will be more difficult to influence Russia by threatening to close its access to Western European markets.
At the height of the debate, Warsaw did not hesitate to compare the Nord Stream as a "new German-Soviet pact", referring to the alliance between Hitler and Stalin to occupy Poland in 1939.
That is, if the issue is politically sensitive.
Western Europe, supporting the Russian project, has obtained greater security of supply.
But the price is a weakening of the energy Europe, since the project has created a gap between Eastern and Western Europeans.
Russia has, in just five years, succeeded in its vision of a direct alliance between Russia and the rich Western countries, large gas consumers and with increasingly limited reserves.
"This pipeline is a component of our partnership with Russia, a new artery that unites us organically," Fillon said during the pipeline's inauguration, demonstrating to what extent major contracts in the gas sector are both political and economic.
All this explains the wide smiles on the faces of Gazprom executives, numerous in Lubmin, at the point of arrival of the gas.
The construction of this pipeline is also a technical achievement.
The submarine tube is made of cement-coated steel to protect it against ship anchors.
It rests on the bottom of the sea, at an average depth of 200 m.
To build it, it was necessary to avoid minefields dating back to World War II.
“It was necessary to remove or destroy a hundred of them, as a precaution,” said Jens M<0xC3><0xBC>ller, spokesman for Nord Stream.
It was also necessary to extend measures to protect fauna and flora.
The tube is a long metal snake that weighs like 242 Eiffel Towers and is not interrupted in its full length: neither by valves nor by maintenance stations.
A control platform was planned in the waters of Sweden, but those responsible for the project gave up on it, seeing that the Swedes were not very willing to allow a Russian state society to be permanently established at sea off its coast.
“In the event of a breakdown, we will interrupt the gas flow in less than a minute,” says Jens M<0xC3><0xBC>ller.
In the event of a leak, the gas from the pipeline will therefore be released into the atmosphere.
But the builders consider it unlikely that a leak will occur, since they have planned joints that, according to forecasts, will have a leak every 100,000 years.
Control of the state of the pipeline is ensured by an underwater robot, carried out by a ship, which carries out external inspections, as well as by a device that circulates through the interior of the pipeline.
In the form of a cigar, it is introduced into the interior of the tube, which has a diameter of one meter, and moves with the gas.
Upon arrival, after three full days of travel at a speed of three meters per second, it provides accurate data on possible deformations of the metal.
The pipeline has been designed to operate for fifty years without the need for any kind of repair.
The circulation of the gas is guaranteed simply by the pressure.
At the beginning it is 200 bars and at the exit of 100 bars.
Five companies have joined forces to carry out this project.
The leading company is Gazprom, which owns 51% of the shares.
It was joined by the German E.ON and BASF (15.5% each), as well as the Dutch Gasunie and the French group GDF Suez (9% each).
These five companies have set up a joint venture, called Nord Stream, to build and operate the pipeline.
It is headquartered in Zug, Switzerland, where taxation is particularly favourable.
Gazprom then leased the entire gas transport capacity to the company for a period of 25 years.
“Gazprom will pay for the full capacity, regardless of how much gas is actually transported,” says Jens M<0xC3><0xBC>ller.
The financing of the construction of the gas pipeline has been completed by 30% with the contribution of the shareholders and by 70% through bank loans.
The total cost of the work should reach 7.4 billion euros for the two tubes.
For GDF Suez, for example, the investment has reached 240 million.
But minority shareholders are confident that they will not exceed their investment, as Gazprom alone assumes the risk of expenses.
The pipeline emerges from the Baltic at Lubmin, on a sandy coast planted with pine trees.
Valves, with a height of 4.5 meters, form the outlet of the gas.
There are sensors that measure the pressure, temperature and specific characteristics of the gas on arrival, before it is transferred to the German gas pipelines.
Since last Tuesday, the terminal receives one million cubic meters of Russian gas every hour.
At full capacity, it will be three million per hour and in 2012, six million.
Moleskine, a brand notebook.
Created half a century ago by an Italian company, Moleskine wants to give people back the taste for writing.
It has an air of adventure, hours of writing in the light of a candle.
The Moleskine notebook is easily recognized, with its rectangular black pastes, its rubber, its leaves of broken white color, as aged by time.
However, the Moleskine notebooks with the current look were born... in 1997.
The Italian company Modo Modo, based in Milan, decided at that time to launch a design notebook, but distinguished.
Maria Sebregondi, then a consultant for the company, was in charge of the launch of the new product.
The notebook is inspired by an old production technique, the mole skin, which refers to a varnished cotton that was used, among other things, to cover the benches.
This type of notebook was highly valued by writers and travelers.
“Moleskine has adapted to the current taste an old and forgotten object, an icon of avant-garde artists until the 20th century,” says Maria Sebregondi, who has since become responsible for the brand in Modo Modo.
And he achieved success.
Between 2006 and 2010, sales increased by 26%, reaching a volume of 12.7 million units sold.
The confidential production of the first years, in which only 3,000 notebooks were designed, has been far behind.
Moleskine goes beyond the Italian borders and exports its products to 70 countries, from France to the United States.
It is difficult to determine the buyer’s profile, since the notebook attracts both businessmen and students and professionals.
Like Moleskine, its users are cosmopolitan, open-minded and cultured.
The small Italian company, which had twelve workers in its beginnings, now owns about 100 and, since 2008, has two offices: one in Milan and the other in New York.
He distributes his notebooks in bookstores, from the Fnac to the small shops in the city center, and has been able to impose his identity.
“We have adapted to the times and the need to write, despite the rise of emails,” explains Maria Sebregondi.
This cultural firm goes hand in hand with the development of Moleskine: recently, the brand has launched the exhibition "Detour" where architects or artists exhibit their own notebook.
In August, he also released a notebook with leopard covers, on the occasion of the Locarno Film Festival.
Taking advantage of its success and this cultural aura, Moleskine has managed to diversify its products: bags, calendars, pens, computer cases... The brand covers a wide range of supports.
