Why is the unemployment rate of disabled workers still so high?
About 19% of people with disabilities are looking for a job.
The 15th Week for the Employment of the Disabled begins today.
Despite a determined public policy, implemented since 2005, the unemployment rate among people with disabilities doubles the average rate: 19%, compared to 9% for the entire population.
Disheartening?
“No,” says <0xC3><0x89>ric Blanchet, CEO of Adapt, the association that organizes the week for the employment of the disabled.
"The progress made over the past 15 years is considerable.
“At the time, the unemployment rate was not twice but three times higher than the average.
"However, there is still a lot to be done."
It is worth noting that the disabled continue to face numerous obstacles to access to employment.
They are usually older: 37% are over 50 years old (an average of 17%).
They have a low level of qualification: 80% have not finished high school and, of the 2.3 million students in higher education, only 10,000 are disabled.
Finally, long-term unemployment is widespread among them: 53% for the disabled, compared with 38% on average.
That is, there are numerous issues that make it especially difficult to return to the world of work and that "constitute the crux of the problem," notes Christian Grapin, CEO of Tremplin, an association created in 1992 to help companies hire disabled workers.
These are the objective obstacles.
In addition, there are those that are not mentioned; the mentality of people advances, but too slowly.
A study conducted in April by the association IMS-Entreprendre for the Cité noted that the surveyed directors have "a low level of knowledge about disabilities", with "an excessive representation of people in wheelchairs, physically or intellectually disabled".
The result: private companies with more than 20 workers are far from the target of hiring 6% of disabled workers, which was set in a 1987 law.
According to the latest available figures, which date back to 2008, they reach a ratio of 2.6%.
“We have now reached around 3%,” says Pierre Blanc, CEO of Agefiph, the agency responsible for collecting contributions from companies that do not respect this law.
The proof: the number of establishments "subject to this contribution", as well as the amounts disbursed, have decreased between 2007 and 2011, from 59,000 to 46,000 structures (and from 606 to 480 million euros).
“The 2005 law, which increased the contributions, has generated a lot of pressure for companies,” explains Pierre Blanc.
“But this improvement also reflects real awareness, particularly among large groups.”
According to the Ministry of Labour, only 59% of companies that have between 20 and 49 workers have disabled employees, compared to 82% of companies with between 100 and 199 workers.
